Markets surged to record highs this week as Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell signaled potential rate cuts at Jackson Hole, boosting investor sentiment across technology and growth stocks. Major developments included significant government intervention in chipmaking, promising AI partnerships, and geopolitical tensions affecting semiconductor supply chains. Here's What We're Covering: • Record market rally driven by Fed dovish signals and rate cut expectations • Major AI partnerships emerge between tech giants Apple and Google • Government stakes in critical semiconductor manufacturing infrastructure • China tensions impact global chip supply chains and production • US business activity accelerates on rising manufacturing demand Dow Hits Record High as Powell Signals September Rate Cut The Dow Jones Industrial Average surged to an all-time high on Friday, climbing 846.24 points, or 1.89%, to close at a record 45,631.74 after Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell signaled potential monetary policy easing next month. The S&P 500 rose 1.52% to 6,466.91, coming within three points of its record high, while the Nasdaq Composite gained 1.88% to finish at 21,496.53. Speaking at the Fed's Jackson Hole conclave, Powell noted that "the baseline outlook and the shifting balance of risks may warrant adjusting our policy stance," citing "sweeping changes" in tax, trade, and immigration policies. Market expectations for a September quarter-point rate cut jumped to roughly 87% from 75% earlier this week, according to CME Group's FedWatch tool. Tesla Surges 6.2% as Powell Signals September Rate Cut Tesla shares soared 6.22% on Friday, leading mega-cap technology stocks higher after Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell delivered dovish remarks at Jackson Hole that boosted expectations for September interest rate cuts. The electric vehicle maker closed at $340.01 with trading volume of $31.2 billion as investors embraced growth stocks amid signals of easier monetary policy ahead. Powell suggested the central bank may lower rates from the current 4.25%-4.50% range, stating "the shifting balance of risks may warrant adjusting our policy stance." The Fed chair's comments sent traders pricing in a 91% chance of a September rate cut, up from 75% before his remarks. Tesla's surge reflected both macroeconomic optimism and company-specific catalysts, including CEO Elon Musk's announcement that Tesla is training a new Full Self-Driving model with nearly ten times more parameters, targeting a major software release by the end of September. Alphabet Shares Jump on Report of Apple AI Partnership Talks Alphabet shares surged more than 3% following reports that Apple is in early discussions to integrate Google's Gemini AI models into an updated version of Siri, the iPhone maker's digital assistant. According to Bloomberg, Apple recently approached Google about building a custom artificial intelligence model to power a revamped Siri that could launch next year. Google's flagship Gemini models have consistently topped AI benchmarks while Apple has struggled to define its own AI strategy. The reported partnership discussions come as Google faces potential regulatory risks to its lucrative search deals with Apple. A US judge is expected to rule this month on penalties for Google's alleged search monopoly, with the Department of Justice recommending the elimination of exclusionary agreements that secure Google's default search position on iPhones and Samsung devices. Apple's Craig Federighi previously indicated the company would consider adding third-party AI models to its Apple Intelligence framework for specific purposes, specifically mentioning Google alongside potential partnerships with Anthropic and OpenAI. US Government Takes 10% Stake in Intel for $8.9 Billion Intel shares rose about 6% after Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick announced the US government has acquired a 10% stake in the embattled chipmaker for $8.9 billion, marking the Trump administration's latest intervention in corporate America. The government purchased 433.3 million Intel shares at $20.47 each, below the current market price, according to the company. Of the total investment, $5.7 billion comes from previously awarded CHIPS Act grants, while $3.2 billion stems from secure chip program funding. "The United States paid nothing for these Shares, and the Shares are now valued at approximately $11 Billion Dollars," President Trump posted on Truth Social, calling it "a great Deal for America and, also, a great Deal for INTEL." The government will hold a warrant for an additional 5% if Intel loses majority control of its foundry business, though it won't receive board representation or governance rights. Intel CEO Lip-Bu Tan emphasized the company's commitment to keeping advanced semiconductor manufacturing in America. Nvidia Halts H20 Chip Production Amid China Security Crackdown Nvidia has asked component suppliers to stop production of its China-focused H20 graphics processing units following Beijing's crackdown on the American chip giant over alleged security concerns, The Information reported on Friday. The directive affects key suppliers, including Arizona-based Amkor Technology, which handles advanced packaging, and South Korea's Samsung Electronics, which provides memory components. Reuters separately reported that Nvidia asked Foxconn to suspend H20-related work. "We constantly manage our supply chain to address market conditions," an Nvidia spokesperson told CNBC. The move comes after China's Cyberspace Administration summoned Nvidia over national security concerns, with Beijing raising questions about potential tracking technology or "backdoors" in the chips. CEO Jensen Huang acknowledged Friday that China had inquired about security backdoors, saying "hopefully the response that we've given to the Chinese government will be sufficient." The development throws doubt on the H20's return to China after Washington recently approved export licenses. Nvidia previously took a $4.5 billion writedown on unsold H20 inventory and said restrictions cost $2.5 billion in quarterly sales. US Business Activity Accelerates in August on Manufacturing Strength US business activity picked up pace in August, led by a resurgent manufacturing sector that posted its strongest order growth in 18 months, according to S&P Global’s flash PMI survey released Thursday. The Composite PMI Output Index, which tracks both manufacturing and services, rose to 55.4 in August from 55.1 in July, the highest since December. A reading above 50 signals expansion. Chris Williamson, chief business economist at S&P Global Market Intelligence, said the data suggested the economy is "expanding at a 2.5% annualized rate, up from the average 1.3% expansion seen over the first two quarters of the year." Manufacturing PMI surged to 53.3 from 49.8 in July — the highest since May 2022 — defying expectations for continued contraction. New order activity also jumped to its strongest level since February 2024. The services PMI eased slightly to 55.4 from 55.7 in July, though still firmly in expansion territory and better than economists’ forecasts of 54.2. The survey noted higher input costs, with the prices-paid index rising to 62.3, its highest in three months, as companies cited new Trump administration tariffs as a key driver. Output prices charged by businesses climbed to a three-year high of 59.3, indicating that firms are increasingly passing on costs to consumers. Employment trends also strengthened, with the composite employment index rising to 52.8, the highest since January, from 51.5 in July.

For example, a product manager may want to query: Find the number of people who live in Bengaluru, travel often, and search for cars. How do you run these queries efficiently? Google Dremel takes advantage of this access pattern: most statistics queries are aggregates like sum, min, max, count . If we store our data in a column-oriented format , running aggregate queries is fast. Dremel is excellent for storing and fetching aggregates. It's also got an optimiser that chooses an execution path (similar to traditional SQL databases). The difference is, Dremel can run on thousands of nodes ! This requires Dremel to use interesting algorithms like Finite Automata and a version of Segment Trees (yeah, you read it right).
